<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[264,1325,505,1411]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[312,414,1265,1290]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Remarks</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[431,553,1265,1290]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insignis">
<emphasis box="[431,553,1265,1290]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">S. insignis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the largest species of the genus occurring in the subcontinent. Its paraphyses are fused for most of their length, a character shared with 
<taxonomicName box="[1117,1241,1305,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutus">
<emphasis box="[1117,1241,1305,1330]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">S. hirsutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName box="[328,449,1345,1370]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scaphoideus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insignis">
<emphasis box="[328,449,1345,1370]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">S. insignis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has entirely different male genitalia, and its male plates have shorter hairlike setae.
</paragraph>
